<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-680-168  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 680 168.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  July 30 1990 v7 n30 p65(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Natural OS/2 stalls over mainframe compatibility need. (SoftwareAG of North America postpones delivery of Natural OS/2 fourthgeneration database language until 3rd quarter 1990)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Software AG of North America Inc postpones delivery of its NaturalOS/2 fourth generation database language until 3rd qtr 1990,citing mainframe compatibility problems as a reason for the delay.andO;The company says its beta testers were clamoring for the fullcommand set offered by the mainframe-based Natural developmentsystem.andP;  Natural OS/2 can create applications for severalthird-party mainframe databases, such as DEC's RMS and Rdb andIBM's DB2, IMS and SQL/DS, as well as for Software AG's Adabase.andO;The current beta version does not support data locking at therecord level, making entire blocks of records inaccessible toother users.andP;  Software AG is also developing Windows 3.0 andPresentation Manager versions of Natural.andP;  Natural OS/2 will sellfor $1,000 for the full development system and $300 for run-timemodules.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Software AG of North America Inc. (product development).andO;Product:   Natural OS/2 (Program development software) (product development).andO;Topic:     Data Base LanguagesFourth-Generation LanguagesProduct DevelopmentProduct Delay.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Citing customer demand for complete mainframe compatibility, Software AG ofNorth America Inc. has postponed delivery of its Natural OS/2fourth-generation database language until late in the third quarter,according to company officials.andM;Software AG pushed back the Natural OS/2 rollout from its originalfirst-quarter delivery date because beta testers were clamoring for a morefunctional product, said Joseph Agro, executive vice president of the Reston,Va., company.andM;The original Natural OS/2 version supported a partial set of commands offeredby Natural on the mainframe, he said.andM;&quot;We originally planned to deliver an OS/2 version that would have been asubset of Natural on the mainframe,&quot; Agro said.andP;  However, when users startedbeta testing Natural OS/2, &quot;they told us they wanted the full set offunctionality, not a subset,&quot; he said.andM;Natural OS/2 can be used to develop applications for Software AG's Adabasemainframe database as well as third-party mainframe databases, includingIBM's DB2, SQL/DS and IMS, and Digital Equipment Corp.'s RMS and Rdb, Agrosaid.andM;Beta testers said the revamped OS/2 product produces code that can betransferred from the PC to the mainframe without changes.andP;  &quot;The codegenerated by the [revamped Natural] OS/2 version is exactly the same as thecode generated on the mainframe,&quot; said OS/2 beta tester Randy Eberling,assistant to the director of data processing at the University of Texas inAustin.andP;  Eberling's group uses both the OS/2 and mainframe flavors of Naturalto develop database applications.andP;  The OS/2 version promises to provide asignificant cost savings by off-loading most of this work from the mainframeto PCs, he said.andM;Natural OS/2 will also incorporate the Adabase database kernel, lettingdevelopers create client/server Adabase applications for PC networks, companyofficials said.andM;One limitation of the system, Eberling noted, is that it doesn't support datalocking at the record level -- it locks out blocks of records instead.andP;  Thismeans that all other records in the block are inaccessible to other users, heexplained.andM;Software AG also plans to develop both Presentation Manager (PM) and Windows3.0 versions of Natural, officials said.andP;  The PM version is due in early1991, the Windows version by fall 1991.andM;Natural OS/2 costs $1,000; run-time modules cost $300.andP;  Software AG can becontacted at (800) 853-9534.andO;</TEXT></DOC>